<section xml:id="sec_limits">
  <title>Limits</title>
  <subsection>
    <title>Recommended Tutorials:</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          \nameref{chp:limits}, pg.
          <xref ref="chp_limits"></xref>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction:</title>
    <p>
      In this activity,
      students will use the <c>limit()</c>
          <idx><h>limit</h></idx>
      command to find various limits.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises:</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to 1} \dfrac{\ln(x^4+1)-1}{x-2}</m>.
          <aside>
            <p>
              There is a shortcut for limits on the palettes toolbar under Calculus.<image width="50%" source="images/palettelimit.png"/>
            </p>
          </aside>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Plot the function
          <me>
            f(x)=\dfrac{|x|}{x}
          </me>
          over an appropriate range, and then use the <c>limit()</c>
            <idx><h>limit</h></idx>
          command to calculate the left-hand limit,
          the right-hand limit, and the two-sided limit as <m>x</m> tends to zero.
          <aside>
            <p>
              In Maple, the absolute value function <m>|\cdot|</m> is denoted as <c>abs( )</c>.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>plot</h><h>discontinuities</h></idx>
          <aside>
            <p>
              Some versions of Maple may not properly display graphs of certain functions that contain discontinuities.
              In this case,
              include <c>discont=true</c> as a parameter in the <c>plot( )</c> command.
            </p>
          </aside>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>g(x)=\dfrac{x^2+x}{\sqrt{x^3+x^2}}</m>.
          <aside>
            <p>
              Use <c>sqrt()</c> to input a square root in Maple.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use the <c>plot()</c> command between <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=2</m> to estimate the left-hand-limit,
                the right-hand limit, and the two-sided limit as <m>x</m> tends to zero.
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    You need to find the limit as <m>x</m> approaches zero,
                    not as it approaches <m>-2</m> or <m>2</m>.
                  </p>
                </aside>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use the <c>limit()</c> command to verify your results from part (a).
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Estimate the value of
          <me>
            \displaystyle\lim_{t\to 0} \dfrac{\sin(t)}{\sin(\pi t)}
          </me>
          by using Maple's <c>plot()</c> command,
          and then check your answer with Maple's <c>limit()</c> command.
          <aside>
            <p>
              Do not forget to use <c>Pi</c> for <m>\pi</m> and include multiplication between <m>\pi</m> and <m>t</m>.
              You will also need to use <m>t</m> instead of <m>x</m> in your <c>plot()</c> command!
            </p>
          </aside>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Calculate <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to \infty} \sqrt{x+1}-x</m>.
            <idx><h>limit</h><h>at infinity</h></idx>
        <aside>
            <p>
              To denote <m>\infty</m> in Maple,
              you need to type the word <c>infinity</c>.
            </p>
          </aside>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the Limit Methods Tutor to explore the steps to calculate
          <me>
            \displaystyle\lim_{x \to -\infty} \sqrt{x^2+x+1}+x
          </me>.
            <idx><h>limit</h><h>at infinity</h></idx>
        <aside>
            <p>
              The Limit Methods Tutor is described on <xref ref="sec_limitmethodstutor">page</xref>.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>limit</h><h>tutor</h></idx>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
</section>